    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-27T08:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-27T08:29:00-05:00" n="134"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d134">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.142/2800</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Petrograd</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-27T16:00:00+02:31">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 27, 1917, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 28, 11.31 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2141. Following message signed “<persName corresp="#p_RL1"
                        >Robins</persName>”<note n="1" xml:id="d134fn1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_RL1">Lieut. Col. Raymond Robins</persName>, in charge
                        of the American Red Cross Commission to Russia.</note> for committee on Red
                    Cross: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>December 26. State Department’s 1920, December 21.<note n="2"
                                xml:id="d134fn2">Not printed; cf. Department’s telegrams No. 1883,
                                Dec. 6, and No. 1917, Dec. 20, and the Ambassador’s telegram No.
                                2091, Dec. 11, <ref target="frus1918Russiav01#pg_289">vol. <hi
                                        rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 289</ref>, <ref
                                    target="frus1918Russiav01#pg_319">319</ref>, and <ref
                                    target="frus1918Russiav01#pg_301">301</ref>.</note> Please urge
                            upon the President the necessity of our continued intercourse with
                            Bolshevik government. Otherwise impossible to arrange for transportation
                            and distribution of supplies, particularly milk. Ambassador approves
                            this statement and has advised State Department to the same effect.
                            Alleged statement of <persName corresp="#p_TL1">Trotsky</persName>,
                            quoted in your message, untrue. Statement made by me to <persName
                                corresp="#p_TL1">Trotsky</persName> was from your cables regarding
                            shipment of supplies.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Please note my approval as stated above.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
